   =20
      Oh Elon: Where we are
   =20
 =20

Let=E2=80=99s just do a roundup of Elon-Musk-buying-Twitter-Inc.-again news=
. First, technically,   the trial=E2=80=99s still on:

The trial in Twitter Inc.=E2=80=99s lawsuit against Elon Musk remains on tr=
ack to begin on Oct. 17 because the court has not yet received an agreement=
 from the parties to put the case on hold, the Delaware judge overseeing th=
e matter said in a letter Wednesday. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CThe parties have not filed a stipulation to stay this action, nor =
has any party moved for a stay,=E2=80=9D Judge Kathaleen St. J. McCormick s=
aid in the Wednesday letter. =E2=80=9CI, therefore, continue to press on to=
ward our trial set to begin on October 17, 2022.=E2=80=9D

Musk has said that he now wants to close the merger on the original terms, =
and Twitter obviously wants that too. There are some much-too-cute ways tha=
t this can end=C2=A0without=C2=A0that happening (mainly: He could be kiddin=
g, or his financing could fall through), and this whole thing has been much=
 too cute and surprised me pretty constantly, so I wouldn=E2=80=99t rule an=
ything out. But probably they will close the merger pretty soon.
There are no real impediments to closing: The deal has gotten the necessary=
 shareholder and regulatory approvals, and Musk=E2=80=99s banks haven=E2=80=
=99t said=C2=A0anything publicly about the financing falling through.=C2=A0=
Still, you have to=C2=A0do=C2=A0the closing. That=E2=80=99s not nothing. Th=
e deal lawyers for Musk and Twitter =E2=80=94=C2=A0not the litigators who h=
ave been fighting each other for months, but the people who wrote the merge=
r agreement back in April when they were friends, and who probably haven=E2=
=80=99t spoken to each other in a while =E2=80=94=C2=A0have to work togethe=
r on a checklist of documents to sign, filings to make=C2=A0and wire transf=
ers to send. Musk has to wire $33.5 billion of his own money, which presuma=
bly is not all in his checking account right now, so he might need some tim=
e to put it in the right accounts. Musk=E2=80=99s bankers have to put up $1=
3 billion of their money, and they will have some processes to do that. Thi=
s could all be done in a few days, but it is work, and everyone has to work=
 together to do it. They might be a bit out of practice.
What Musk apparently wants is to pause the trial while they can work this a=
ll out:  He offered to =E2=80=9Cproceed to closing of the transaction,=E2=
=80=9D but only =E2=80=9Cprovided that the Delaware Chancery Court enter an=
 immediate stay of the action ...=C2=A0and adjourn the trial.=E2=80=9D What=
 Twitter wants is sort of the opposite, to keep the pressure of a trial on =
Musk until he shows up with the money. This feels like a solvable problem =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0basically, you write some sort of agreement that says like =
=E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re going to work together to get the closing done this =
week, but if we don=E2=80=99t we=E2=80=99re gonna have an extra-super-bad t=
rial,=E2=80=9D and you get Chancellor McCormick to bless it =E2=80=94 but t=
hey=C2=A0have to work together to solve it. They have to negotiate and draf=
t an Agreement to Stick to the=C2=A0Agreement. If you=E2=80=99re writing th=
at agreement, you have some trust issues.
The Wall Street Journal  reports:
As of late Wednesday, representatives of Mr. Musk and Twitter were trying t=
o hash out the details of his proposal this week to stick to that original =
agreement, the people familiar with the matter said. Sticking points includ=
e what would be required from both sides for litigation over the stalled de=
al to be dropped and whether the deal=E2=80=99s closing would be contingent=
 on Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s receiving the necessary debt financing, some of the =
people said.
Under the terms of the original agreement, the closing=C2=A0was=C2=A0more o=
r less contingent on the debt financing: If Musk=E2=80=99s banks did not co=
me up with the $13 billion they have promised, Musk did not have to close, =
though he would have to pay a $1 billion termination fee. Under the current=
 circumstances, I don=E2=80=99t think that either Twitter or a judge would =
be very satisfied with that result. I don=E2=80=99t think the lawsuit is go=
ing to be dropped until Twitter is sure that the banks will fund.
One notable deadline for resolving this was=C2=A0today, when Musk was suppo=
sed to have his deposition in the lawsuit, but I guess   that=E2=80=99s on =
hold now:
Elon Musk won=E2=80=99t be showing up Thursday for a long-awaited depositio=
n in Twitter Inc.=E2=80=99s lawsuit aimed at forcing him to go through with=
 a $44 billion buyout of the company, according to people familiar with the=
 matter. ... The deposition was scheduled to start at 9:30 a.m. at a law fi=
rm=E2=80=99s offices in Austin, Texas.
The simplest reading of the situation=C2=A0is that he paid $44 billion to g=
et out of having to do that deposition.

