When Musk signed his deal to buy Twitter, it was very important to Twitter =
that he had $46.5 billion of money lined up to pay for the purchase price, =
various closing costs, etc.=C2=A0This money   came from two places:
=09His banks, led by Morgan Stanley, committed to provide $13 billion of de=
bt financing.=C2=A0=09Musk promised to provide the other $33.5 billion from=
 his personal wealth.

That oversimplifies a bit; in fact, initially Musk only committed to put up=
 $21 billion of cash, with the remaining $12.5 billion coming from a margin=
 loan that some of his banks agreed to provide against his Tesla Inc. share=
s. But in practice that=E2=80=99s all the same pot of money. Musk=E2=80=99s=
 liquid wealth consists mostly of Tesla stock, and to come up with $33.5 bi=
llion he would need to either (1) sell $33.5 billion of Tesla stock, (2) pu=
t $167.5 billion of Tesla stock in hock to borrow $33.5 billion against it,
  [1]
=C2=A0or (3) some combination thereof. The initial proposal was =E2=80=9Cso=
me combination thereof,=E2=80=9D but over time it shifted, and eventually h=
e   got rid of the margin loan entirely. (Simplistically, if you sell $5 of=
 Tesla stock you get $5; if you borrow against $5 of Tesla stock you get=C2=
=A0$1. As Tesla stock fell, Musk had less capacity to borrow, and had to ge=
t more of his money from selling.)
But it was always Musk=E2=80=99s plan=C2=A0not=C2=A0to fund that full $33.5=
 billion out of his personal wealth. He was allowed to, and tried to, and d=
id, replace some of the $33.5 billion of his personal funds with other mone=
y. Most notably he   raised about $7.1 billion of equity commitments from a=
n assortment of investors who had his phone number (Larry Ellison, Andreess=
en Horowitz, Qatar Holdings, Fidelity, etc.), and strongly hinted that he w=
as looking for more. Those investors were signing up for the same deal he w=
as: They put in cash to buy Twitter shares at $54.20 per share, and if Musk=
 succeeds in making it more valuable, they all=C2=A0get rich.
But there is an important difference between those people and Musk=E2=80=99=
s banks. Those people promised to give Musk $7.1 billion to buy Twitter, bu=
t that=E2=80=99s none of Twitter=E2=80=99s concern: If they flake, Musk sti=
ll has to cover the $33.5 billion. He has a binding equity commitment to pu=
t up $33.5 billion of his own money; if he can get some of it from other in=
vestors, Twitter is fine with that, but if he can=E2=80=99t that=E2=80=99s =
his problem.=C2=A0
The banks are different. Their $13 billion=C2=A0commitment=C2=A0is real and=
 binding=C2=A0and Twitter relied on it in signing the merger agreement. Mus=
k=E2=80=99s banks have very few ways out of that commitment. They wish they=
 did =E2=80=94=C2=A0they are looking at hundreds of millions, perhaps billi=
ons of dollars of losses from funding these loans on terms that they agreed=
 to in April =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that is life in the leveraged finance busin=
ess; debt commitments are meant to be commitments. But if somehow the banks=
 don=E2=80=99t fund their $13 billion, that=E2=80=99s Twitter=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0problem: Musk doesn=E2=80=99t have to close the deal, because=C2=A0his c=
ommitment is capped at $33.5 billion. This oversimplifies, and if Musk were=
 to=C2=A0tell=C2=A0his banks not to fund their $13 billion he might get int=
o, you know, $46.5 billion worth of trouble, but it=E2=80=99s basically cor=
rect. Twitter has a deal to get $46.5 billion, with $33.5 billion of it fro=
m Musk and $13 billion from his banks.
And so yesterday   I speculated about three questions:
=09Will Musk=E2=80=99s banks fund their $13 billion? I think they will. But=
 if they don=E2=80=99t, he won=E2=80=99t have enough money to close the dea=
l, and it will be a huge mess. Perhaps he=E2=80=99ll be able to get out of =
the deal by paying a $1 billion termination fee, or perhaps he will be forc=
ed to sue the banks to get them to fund, or perhaps the judge   will order =
him to pay the $13 billion out of his own cash, and all of it will be litig=
ated bitterly.=09Will Musk=E2=80=99s friends fund their $7.1 billion of equ=
ity? I have no idea, and I think they have decent arguments that they don=
=E2=80=99t have to anymore, though I think that this is mostly a question=
=C2=A0of reputation and friendships rather than legal arguments. (I doubt M=
usk would sue if they don=E2=80=99t pay, but he could make their lives unpl=
easant in other ways.) But also I don=E2=80=99t think it=C2=A0matters:=C2=
=A0The deal will close whether or not any of Musk=E2=80=99s equity investor=
s put in money. It=E2=80=99s just a question of whether Musk has to write a=
 check for $26 billion or $33.5 billion or something in between.=09Will Mus=
k find=C2=A0other=C2=A0equity investors? He sold about $7.1 billion of equi=
ty to his friends back in April and May, when he liked the deal. Then he st=
opped, because he was trying to get out. Now he likes the deal again: Will =
he find some more investors, so that he only has to write a $20 billion che=
