<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When Musk signed his deal to buy Twitter, it w=
as very important to Twitter that he had $46.5 billion of money lined up to=
 pay for the purchase price, various closing costs, etc.=C2=A0This money <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29286274.284524/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjEvZWxvbi1=
nb3QtaGlzLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMDYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haW=
wmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAwNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZ=
XlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB76474626" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  came from two places=
</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">His banks, led by Morgan Stanley, com=
mitted to provide $13 billion of debt financing.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Musk promised to provide the other $33.5 billion from =
his personal wealth.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That oversimplifies a bit; in fact, initially =
Musk only committed to put up $21 billion of cash, with the remaining $12.5=
 billion coming from a margin loan that some of his banks agreed to provide=
 against his Tesla Inc. shares. But in practice that=E2=80=99s all the same=
 pot of money. Musk=E2=80=99s liquid wealth consists mostly of Tesla stock,=
 and to come up with $33.5 billion he would need to either (1) sell $33.5 b=
illion of Tesla stock, (2) put $167.5 billion of Tesla stock in hock to bor=
row $33.5 billion against it,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0or (3) some combination thereof. The initial proposal was =E2=80=
=9Csome combination thereof,=E2=80=9D but over time it shifted, and eventua=
lly he <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29286274.28=
4524/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMj=
YvZWxvbi1jYWxsZWQtb2ZmLWhpcy1tYXJnaW4tbG9hbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDA2MjJfTU9ORVlTV=
FVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEw=
MDYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9dc37e8c" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">  got rid of the margin loan entirely</a>. (Simplistically, if you sell=
 $5 of Tesla stock you get $5; if you borrow against $5 of Tesla stock you =
get=C2=A0$1. As Tesla stock fell, Musk had less capacity to borrow, and had=
 to get more of his money from selling.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it was always Musk=E2=80=99s plan=C2=A0<em=
>not=C2=A0</em>to fund that full $33.5 billion out of his personal wealth. =
He was allowed to, and tried to, and did, replace some of the $33.5 billion=
 of his personal funds with other money. Most notably he <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29286274.284524/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMDkvbXVzay10d2l0dGVyLWhhcy1=
uZXctb3duZXJzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMDYyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdX=
RtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAwNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzd=
HVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB58fc8318" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  raised about $7.1 bill=
ion of equity commitments</a> from an assortment of investors who had his p=
hone number (Larry Ellison, Andreessen Horowitz, Qatar Holdings, Fidelity, =
etc.), and strongly hinted that he was looking for more. Those investors we=
re signing up for the same deal he was: They put in cash to buy Twitter sha=
res at $54.20 per share, and if Musk succeeds in making it more valuable, t=
hey all=C2=A0get rich.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is an important difference between t=
hose people and Musk=E2=80=99s banks. Those people promised to give Musk $7=
.1 billion to buy Twitter, but that=E2=80=99s none of Twitter=E2=80=99s con=
cern: If they flake, Musk still has to cover the $33.5 billion. He has a bi=
nding equity commitment to put up $33.5 billion of his own money; if he can=
 get some of it from other investors, Twitter is fine with that, but if he =
can=E2=80=99t that=E2=80=99s his problem.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The banks are different. Their $13 billion=C2=
=A0commitment=C2=A0is real and binding=C2=A0and Twitter relied on it in sig=
ning the merger agreement. Musk=E2=80=99s banks have very few ways out of t=
hat commitment. They wish they did =E2=80=94=C2=A0they are looking at hundr=
eds of millions, perhaps billions of dollars of losses from funding these l=
oans on terms that they agreed to in April =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that is life =
in the leveraged finance business; debt commitments are meant to be commitm=
ents. But if somehow the banks don=E2=80=99t fund their $13 billion, that=
=E2=80=99s <em>Twitter=E2=80=99s=C2=A0</em>problem: Musk doesn=E2=80=99t ha=
ve to close the deal, because=C2=A0his commitment is capped at $33.5 billio=
n. This oversimplifies, and if Musk were to=C2=A0<em>tell=C2=A0</em>his ban=
ks not to fund their $13 billion he might get into, you know, $46.5 billion=
 worth of trouble, but it=E2=80=99s basically correct. Twitter has a deal t=
o get $46.5 billion, with $33.5 billion of it from Musk and $13 billion fro=
m his banks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so yesterday <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/29286274.284524/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMDUvZWxvbi1zLWJhY2s_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAwNj=
IyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX=
3Rlcm09MjIxMDA2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCa8=
14e90c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">  I speculated</a> about three questions:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Will Musk=E2=80=99s banks fund their =
$13 billion? I think they will. But if they don=E2=80=99t, he won=E2=80=99t=
 have enough money to close the deal, and it will be a huge mess. Perhaps h=
e=E2=80=99ll be able to get out of the deal by paying a $1 billion terminat=
ion fee, or perhaps he will be forced to sue the banks to get them to fund,=
 or perhaps the judge <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/29286274.284524/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjItMDctMTIvaS13YXMtdG9sZC10aGVyZS1kLWJlLWEtY2FrZS1tZXJnZXI_Y21waWQ9Qk=
JEMTAwNjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0Z=
XImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMDA2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBa577824c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  will order him</a> to pay the $13 billion out of =
his own cash, and all of it will be litigated bitterly.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">Will Musk=E2=80=99s friends fund their $7.1 billion o=
f equity? I have no idea, and I think they have decent arguments that they =
don=E2=80=99t have to anymore, though I think that this is mostly a questio=
n=C2=A0of reputation and friendships rather than legal arguments. (I doubt =
Musk would sue if they don=E2=80=99t pay, but he could make their lives unp=
leasant in other ways.) But also I don=E2=80=99t think it=C2=A0<em>matters:=
=C2=A0</em>The deal will close whether or not any of Musk=E2=80=99s equity =
investors put in money. It=E2=80=99s just a question of whether Musk has to=
 write a check for $26 billion or $33.5 billion or something in between.</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Will Musk find=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0<=
/em>equity investors? He sold about $7.1 billion of equity to his friends b=
ack in April and May, when he liked the deal. Then he stopped, because he w=
as trying to get out. Now he likes the deal again: Will he find some more i=
nvestors, so that he only has to write a $20 billion check instead of $26 b=
illion? This question is essentially the same as the previous one. It doesn=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>matter=C2=A0</em>for getting the deal done; Musk is com=
mitted for the full $33.5 billion, and he has the money. Maybe he=E2=80=99l=
l do it alone, or maybe he=E2=80=99ll do it with the $7.1 billion he raised=
 from his friends in April and May, or maybe they=E2=80=99ll abandon him bu=
t he=E2=80=99ll raise another $7=C2=A0billion from different investors this=
 afternoon, or maybe both, or some other combination.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk also spent some time, in May, in the coup=
le of weeks between when he signed the agreement and when he started trying=
 to get out of it, trying to raise=C2=A0<em>preferred=C2=A0</em>equity. The=
 rough way the preferred equity works is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You give Elon Musk, say, $5 billion to=
 buy Twitter.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Musk takes about thr=
ee years to turn Twitter around as a private company, solve the bot problem=
, make it an everything app, whatever.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">Then he takes it public again.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;=
">If it=E2=80=99s worth at least, say, $22 billion when he takes it public =
again =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, if he=E2=80=99s made it more valuable, or kep=
t it=C2=A0<em>as=C2=A0</em>valuable, or destroyed less than half of its exi=
sting value =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you get back $7.5 billion, a nice 50% retur=
n for three years of risk.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importan=
t; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0(If the value is=C2=A0<em>up</em>, maybe you get even more.<a cla=
ss=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent=
 !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If it takes him longer to ge=
t back to the public markets, you get more. (Though you have taken more ris=
k.) If it takes five years, maybe you get back $10 billion. The amount you =
get back grows each year.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If Musk =
instead incinerates the company while he controls it, then you get=C2=A0not=
hing.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a more-or-less fixed-income security, =
like a very risky bond, and Musk was apparently marketing it to credit inve=
stors who like to live dangerously. Specifically, Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Heath=
er Perlberg <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/292862=
